title: For Sale/Trade:  L3 insight mini thermal monocular MTM AN/PAS-23 FLIR
postcontent:
Used less than 5 hours, these are the civilian version of the military's an/pas-23 thermal monocular. Manufactured by L3 Insight, the makers of eotech sights, this thermal handheld monocular is amazing for finding living heat signatures in total darkness or in full sunlight. This unit is about the size of a can of beer and weighs under 12 ounces. It has 2 power zoom and white hot/black hot functions. The IR laser works great for two man teams. The person with thermal can scan an area and if they find a heat signature they can use the invisible IR laser to show a team member using night vision where the heat is located. If you ever night hog or coyote hunt, these will up your game. Or even use them to spot other game pre dawn. The tactical applications are endless. 
Includes all the original accessories including remote pressure switch for IR laser and down loading cable to transfer still photos from the unit to your computer. 
Please google and see what they retail for new. My price is well below half of retail.

title: For Sale:  Looking for a .380 or 38 special?
location: NW San Antonio, San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
They’re fine guns (sometimes). But, they’re usually pretty expensive and the value doesn’t keep going up, just down. It’s a lot like driving a car off the lot.
I recommend a Makarov or a Makarov type of pistol. They’re more powerful, hold more ammo (higher capacity) and much more accurate than any .380 and they’re as powerful as, maybe even more powerful than as 38 Special Snub noses. The 38 special long barrels and 38 special +P are a little more powerful, though. But, the Maks are much more accurate and also have a higher capacity. And, since Maks are Military and Police Grade weapons, they never jam. No failure to feed or eject. 38 special snub noses and 380 don’t get enough speed coming out the short barrels to expand hollow points. So you might has well be shooting FMJ.
I have a very rare German Makarov ($600) and a FEG PA-63 ($350).  Both shoot the great 9 X 18 Makarov ammo. Academy has round nose FMJ, box of 50 for $10.99 and Hornedy JHP box of 20 or 25 for $20. So, ammo is no longer hard to find. Maks price are going up and up and up.  Go to gunbroker.com. Enter Makarov.  They’re cheap. That is until the last day or hours of the bids. Then you’ll see how much they really cost. Then you add taxes, shipping and the cost of getting the gun from a FFL. You can add another $80 to $100 to the shown cost.
I’m open to offers or trade, but don’t get ridiculous. 
Armslist will only allow me to upload one picture. So if you want a picture of The FEG PA-63, you can either look further on Armslist (I have it posted separately), or you can request it, and I'll send it to you.

Starting with a Limited Deluxe, takedown Winchester 1886, Turnbull converted this modern rifle to its original platform, making it a TRUE Winchester 1886 Deluxe takedown. To do so, the good folks at Turnbull Mfg. removed the top tang safety and filled the opening—eliminating the tang safety. They then converted the hammer to the original half-cock style safety notch, and the firing pin was converted, too. The receiver, hammer, lever and forend cap are finished with traditional Bone Charcoal Color Case Hardening. Some of the finer parts were then fire-blued. In addition to the coloring, the rifle received their trademark flattop rear sight, an option that helps in quick sight acquisition. title: For Sale:  MAB Brevete Model A Type I I First Variant
postcontent:
This pistol was manufactured sometime between 1940 and 1944 in France during the German occupation before WW II.  The Type II Model A has a nickel-finish, a striker-fired, single-action 6.35 cal, with a six-round magazine capacity.   A unique feature on the first variant of the Type II Model A is the design of the firing pin spring guide, which has a small pin projecting at a right angle from its rear section.  This pin locks into a recess in the top of the slide and prevents the striker and spring from flying out when the slide is removed froom the frame.

The pistol has some wear on the nickel plating and could use a deep cleaning.  Other than those minor cosmetic issues, it is in excellent working order.  It has been fired within the last year and comes with a 50 round (minus 4 ) box of .25 cal ammunition.   I am asking $250 (OBO)

title: For Sale:  FN FNH USA 9mm model FNS9 Stainless Lever Safety 18 Shot Black 3 Magazines Fabrique Nationale Herstal USA 66926
postcontent:
Seller Stock #: HG66926 

Here is FN’s front runner, the FNS9 pistol. Type is striker fired semi automatic pistol. Chambering is 9mm Luger, 9mm Parabellum, 9x19, call it what you will, THE 9mm. Manufacturer is FNH USA, with production facilities in Columbia, South Carolina. Construction is stainless steel barrel and slide, with steel internal parts that include its full length guide rod, all housed in a high impact polymer frame. Barrel is 4 inch cold hammer forged, 1:9.84 right hand conventional six groove rifling with polished feed ramp. Slide is matte stainless, serrated fore and aft. Sights are dovetailed front and rear, 3 dot combat factory issue anodized alloy, drift adjustable for windage only. Trigger is .375 smooth faced two piece, 1/2 inch two stage 8 pound pull. Mechanism is striker fired, full time double action, with reset upon slide return. Safety system consists of trigger safety, internal drop and firing pin safety, with low profile manually operated ambidextrous lever safety. The FNS does Not have a magazine safety. Magazine release is fully ambidextrous. Magazines are serratted steel bodied smooth finish dark stainless steel with welded back sides, steel springs, and polymer floorplate and cartridge follower. Each magazine holds 17 rounds of 9mm caliber ammunition, so 17+1 fully loaded capacity, and each mag is ported for visible round count. Frame incorporates a 4 slot Mil-Standard M13 Picatinny rail for light or accessory. Safety lever, magazine release, and slide stop are all ambidextrous with no need for modification for left handed shooters. Disassembly is achieved with a slotted lever and dry fire disconnection. Grip frame comes with a total of two interchangeable mainspring housings or back straps, to adjust the grip circumference. Overall length is 7 1/4 inches from the barrel muzzle to the tail of the grip frame strut. Height is 5 1/2 inches from the top of the rear sight to the bottom of the magazine floorplate. Lateral frame thickness is 1.20 at the ejection port including the lever. Weight empty is 24.5 ounces, with center of gravity at the back top of trigger, or 33 ounces fully loaded with 180s and centered at the back of the magazine release. Each FNS9 comes in its original factory box with a total of 3 magazines, total of 2 backstrap panels, instruction manual, factory registration card, cable lock, and fired brass envelope.
